        <mxCell id="B_A-7dZrPUxgCriRJH3T-83" parent="1" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" value="&lt;h1 style=&quot;margin-top: 0px;&quot;&gt;VM CPU Performance Troubleshooting&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;There are 4 primary metrics proving that a VM does not get the CPU it demands. Primary metrics are explained by secondary metrics. For a single VM troubleshooting, check the VM itself, its parent ESXi, and&amp;nbsp; Cluster-setting such as Resource Pools and VM-Host Affinity. Factors outside the VM is shown as box with&amp;nbsp;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=&quot;color: rgb(50, 43, 255);&quot;&gt;shadow&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This is a flow diagram. &lt;b&gt;&lt;font style=&quot;color: rgb(4, 96, 255);&quot;&gt;Follow &lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;the arrow to go deeper or further into the root cause.&lt;/p&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="120" width="1120" x="40" y="-30" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="r-Z9p2JSx4lLs6wgrhMz-1" parent="1" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;rounded=0;" value="The problem. Only 4 metrics define the problem. All others are supporting, secondary metrics. Ignore CPU Latency counter, as that&#39;s for VMkernel CPU scheduler, not human operator" vertex="1">
