        <mxCell id="gFa9RxsSB_Rw88-SS1sg-13" parent="1" style="text;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;" value="&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Helvetica; font-size: 12px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial; float: none; display: inline !important;&quot;&gt;This diagram only covers VM. Guest OS has its own troubleshooting flow, and it uses Windows or Linux specific counters. Ensure both BIOS &amp;amp; Guest OS areoptimized for virtualization.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Helvetica; font-size: 12px; font-style: normal; font-variant-ligatures: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: 2; text-align: left; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; widows: 2; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; white-space: normal; text-decoration-thickness: initial; text-decoration-style: initial; text-decoration-color: initial; float: none; display: inline !important;&quot;&gt;Logically, cluster level setting such as DRS plays a part. See the Cluster diagram as no point duplicating.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;" vertex="1">
